1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,323
If you asked an artificial intelligence to

2
00:00:02,323 --> 00:00:04,646
grade its own writing, you'd probably expect

3
00:00:04,646 --> 00:00:07,301
it to be a little generous with itself.

4
00:00:07,301 --> 00:00:08,628
Most of them are.

5
00:00:08,628 --> 00:00:10,288
But one of them isn't.

6
00:00:10,288 --> 00:00:12,611
One of them looks at its own

7
00:00:12,611 --> 00:00:15,929
work and gives it lower marks than anyone else does.

8
00:00:15,929 --> 00:00:17,257
So here's the question.

9
00:00:17,257 --> 00:00:19,248
Is that AI being unusually honest?

10
00:00:19,248 --> 00:00:21,240
Or is it just genuinely worse?

11
00:00:21,239 --> 00:00:24,883
We ran a study where four AI models — Claude,

12
00:00:24,883 --> 00:00:27,434
Gemini, GPT, and Kimi — each wrote

13
00:00:27,434 --> 00:00:29,985
answers to the same set of prompts,

14
00:00:29,985 --> 00:00:33,629
and then each model graded all four sets of answers.

15
00:00:33,629 --> 00:00:34,722
Including its own.

16
00:00:34,722 --> 00:00:38,002
This gives us a clean way to measure self-preference.

17
00:00:38,002 --> 00:00:40,552
Compare the score a model gives its

18
00:00:40,552 --> 00:00:43,103
own answer to the score the other

19
00:00:43,103 --> 00:00:45,290
three judges give that same answer.

20
00:00:45,290 --> 00:00:47,111
The gap is the favoritism.

21
00:00:47,111 --> 00:00:51,144
Three of the four models behaved the way you'd expect.

22
00:00:51,144 --> 00:00:53,967
Claude rated its own writing about two

23
00:00:53,967 --> 00:00:57,597
and a half points higher than its peers did.

24
00:00:57,597 --> 00:01:00,823
GPT, about one and a third points higher.

25
00:01:00,823 --> 00:01:03,646
Gemini, a smaller but still positive bump

26
00:01:03,646 --> 00:01:06,066
of two thirds of a point.

27
00:01:06,066 --> 00:01:07,679
Different sizes, same direction.

28
00:01:07,679 --> 00:01:09,695
Self-flattery in three different shades.

29
00:01:09,695 --> 00:01:10,842
Then there's Kimi.

30
00:01:10,842 --> 00:01:13,516
Kimi rated its own writing nearly three

31
00:01:13,516 --> 00:01:16,572
full points lower than the other judges did.

32
00:01:16,572 --> 00:01:20,011
A self-preference score of minus two point eight seven.

33
00:01:20,011 --> 00:01:23,067
This is the opposite of every other model.

34
00:01:23,067 --> 00:01:26,505
On a coin that has self-love on one side,

35
00:01:26,505 --> 00:01:28,415
Kimi landed on the other.

36
00:01:28,415 --> 00:01:30,907
There are two ways to read this.

37
00:01:30,907 --> 00:01:34,465
Maybe Kimi is the most honest evaluator in the group,

38
00:01:34,465 --> 00:01:36,956
willing to give itself the low marks

39
00:01:36,956 --> 00:01:39,091
the others can't bring themselves to.

40
00:01:39,091 --> 00:01:41,938
Or maybe Kimi's own answers really are weaker,

41
00:01:41,938 --> 00:01:45,497
and Kimi simply has better judgment about its own quality.

42
00:01:45,497 --> 00:01:49,055
We can actually tell the two apart with the data.

43
00:01:49,055 --> 00:01:50,251
Here's the tell.

44
00:01:50,251 --> 00:01:54,236
Look at how the other three judges scored Kimi's answers.

45
00:01:54,236 --> 00:01:57,026
The average is around five point two,

46
00:01:57,026 --> 00:01:59,018
on a ten point scale.

47
00:01:59,018 --> 00:02:01,011
The other three models' answers,

48
00:02:01,011 --> 00:02:04,996
scored by the same judges, sit between eight and nine.

49
00:02:04,996 --> 00:02:07,387
This is not a close call.

50
00:02:07,387 --> 00:02:10,176
The peer consensus is that Kimi's answers

51
00:02:10,176 --> 00:02:12,966
genuinely score lower in this evaluation setup.

52
00:02:12,966 --> 00:02:15,357
The other judges aren't being mean.

53
00:02:15,357 --> 00:02:17,349
They agree across the board.

54
00:02:17,349 --> 00:02:19,740
So Kimi's low self-score isn't humility.

55
00:02:19,740 --> 00:02:20,936
It's largely accuracy.

56
00:02:20,936 --> 00:02:25,319
Kimi can see the same quality gap that everyone else sees.

57
00:02:25,319 --> 00:02:27,626
We can go one level deeper.

58
00:02:27,626 --> 00:02:30,318
Break the scores down by rubric and

59
00:02:30,318 --> 00:02:32,624
the gap concentrates in one place.

60
00:02:32,624 --> 00:02:35,700
On the criterion called constraint adherence — basically,

61
00:02:35,700 --> 00:02:38,391
did the answer follow the format the

62
00:02:38,391 --> 00:02:42,620
prompt asked for — Kimi penalizes itself by almost five points.

63
00:02:42,620 --> 00:02:45,312
And by task category, the gap is

64
00:02:45,312 --> 00:02:47,234
biggest in logic and math.

65
00:02:47,234 --> 00:02:50,310
Five and a half points lower on logic.

66
00:02:50,310 --> 00:02:53,001
Four and a half lower on math.

67
00:02:53,001 --> 00:02:56,077
On softer prose tasks, the gap is small.

68
00:02:56,077 --> 00:02:58,768
This isn't a global sense of inadequacy.

69
00:02:58,768 --> 00:02:59,537
It's targeted.

70
00:02:59,537 --> 00:03:01,459
Kimi is, in this setup,

71
00:03:01,459 --> 00:03:04,919
weaker on the strict-format tasks, and Kimi knows it.

72
00:03:04,919 --> 00:03:07,989
Now the part that complicates the honesty story.

73
00:03:07,989 --> 00:03:09,908
If Kimi were simply unbiased,

74
00:03:09,908 --> 00:03:12,594
you'd expect its scores of the other

75
00:03:12,594 --> 00:03:14,512
three models to be even-handed.

76
00:03:14,512 --> 00:03:15,280
They aren't.

77
00:03:15,280 --> 00:03:19,117
When we measure Kimi's biases toward the other three models,

78
00:03:19,117 --> 00:03:21,035
one of them stands out.

79
00:03:21,035 --> 00:03:23,721
Kimi has a measurable preference for Claude.

80
00:03:23,721 --> 00:03:26,023
Plus three tenths of a point,

81
00:03:26,023 --> 00:03:29,093
every time Claude's name is in the byline.

82
00:03:29,093 --> 00:03:30,628
So Kimi isn't bias-free.

83
00:03:30,628 --> 00:03:32,163
Kimi is differently biased.

84
00:03:32,163 --> 00:03:36,383
Less self-love, but a soft spot for one of its peers.

85
00:03:36,383 --> 00:03:38,865
This is the lesson worth holding onto.

86
00:03:38,865 --> 00:03:40,992
Self-preference and accuracy are not opposites.

87
00:03:40,992 --> 00:03:43,474
A model can rate itself low because

88
00:03:43,474 --> 00:03:45,956
it really is weaker, and a model

89
00:03:45,956 --> 00:03:49,147
can rate itself high because it really is stronger,

90
00:03:49,147 --> 00:03:51,628
and in both cases the score has

91
00:03:51,628 --> 00:03:53,401
nothing to do with honesty.

92
00:03:53,401 --> 00:03:57,301
What gives the bias away is the structure of the errors.

93
00:03:57,301 --> 00:03:59,074
Where does the over-scoring happen.

94
00:03:59,074 --> 00:04:01,555
Which peers does the model lean toward.

95
00:04:01,555 --> 00:04:04,391
What kinds of tasks bring the gap out.

96
00:04:04,391 --> 00:04:07,162
When you see one model behave dramatically

97
00:04:07,162 --> 00:04:09,933
differently from the others in an evaluation,

98
00:04:09,933 --> 00:04:13,496
the temptation is to call it the honest one.

99
00:04:13,496 --> 00:04:14,288
The contrarian.

100
00:04:14,288 --> 00:04:15,080
The truth-teller.

101
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:16,267
Sometimes that's right.

102
00:04:16,267 --> 00:04:19,038
More often, the outlier just has a

103
00:04:19,038 --> 00:04:21,017
different mix of strengths, weaknesses,

104
00:04:21,017 --> 00:04:24,580
and quiet preferences than the rest of the group.

105
00:04:24,580 --> 00:04:28,539
The interesting models aren't the ones who like themselves more.

106
00:04:28,539 --> 00:04:32,101
They're the ones whose errors give away their structure.

107
00:04:32,101 --> 00:04:36,060
The full study, with all the data, is linked below.

108
00:04:36,060 --> 00:04:37,247
Thanks for watching.
